<DocsLayout
  title="OBS browser sources"
  description="Add ilyStream widgets and alerts to OBS as transparent browser sources so they composite cleanly with your scenes."
  slug="obs"
  updated="May 2026"
  readingTime="7 min"
  toc={toc}
>
  <h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>
  <p>
    ilyStream serves widgets and alerts over a small local HTTP server. To use them
    in OBS you add them as <strong>Browser Sources</strong>. This guide covers
    starting the server, adding the source, and the small CSS detail that keeps the
    background transparent so overlays composite cleanly with your camera.
  </p>

  <h2 id="prerequisites">Prerequisites</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>OBS Studio 28 or newer.</li>
    <li>ilyStream running on the same machine as OBS (recommended) or on the same LAN.</li>
    <li>Your stream PC's firewall allows local HTTP traffic on the overlay port.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="start-server">Start the overlay server</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Open the Widgets workspace.</strong> ilyStream's overlay server starts automatically when the app launches, but the URLs live here.</li>
    <li><strong>Note the port.</strong> The status bar shows the overlay URL (e.g. <code>http://127.0.0.1:7100</code>). Open <em>Settings &rarr; Overlays</em> to change it.</li>
    <li><strong>Pick the widget you want.</strong> Each widget shows its own URL with the widget id appended.</li>
    <li><strong>Copy the URL.</strong> Use the copy button in the widget card.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2 id="add-source">Add a Browser Source in OBS</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Select the scene.</strong> In OBS, pick the scene that should display the overlay.</li>
    <li><strong>Add a Browser Source.</strong> Click <em>+</em> in the Sources list and choose <em>Browser</em>. Name it something descriptive (e.g. "ilyStream alerts").</li>
    <li>
      <strong>Paste the URL.</strong> Set:
      <ul>
        <li><strong>URL</strong>: the URL you copied from ilyStream.</li>
        <li><strong>Width</strong>: 1920 (or your canvas width).</li>
        <li><strong>Height</strong>: 1080.</li>
        <li><strong>FPS</strong>: 60. Lower if CPU is tight.</li>
      </ul>
    </li>
    <li><strong>Leave the Custom CSS field empty for now.</strong> Most ilyStream widgets ship with a transparent body already.</li>
    <li><strong>Click OK.</strong> The widget renders into your scene.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2 id="transparent">Transparent backgrounds</h2>
  <p>
    OBS browser sources default to a transparent background, but if your widget
    shows a black box you can force it with a one-line CSS override:
  </p>
  <pre><code>{`body { background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0) !important; margin: 0; }`}</code></pre>
  <p>
    Paste that into the <em>Custom CSS</em> field of the Browser Source. Useful if
    you've nested your own HTML wrapper around an ilyStream widget.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <span class="callout__icon">i</span>
    <p><strong>Once per source.</strong> OBS keeps custom CSS per-source, so each browser source can override its own background independently.</p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="sizing">Sizing &amp; layering</h2>
  <p>Two practical patterns cover most overlays:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Full-canvas overlays.</strong> Set the source size to your canvas resolution and pin it at <code>0,0</code>. The widget itself positions content.</li>
    <li><strong>Component overlays.</strong> Set the source size to just the area the widget covers (e.g. 480&times;120 for a chat box) and place it on the canvas. Easier to nudge.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Layer alerts on top of camera and scene art. Pin them above your camera source
    so animation never gets clipped by mid-scene transitions.
  </p>

  <h3>Refreshing after edits</h3>
  <p>
    When you tweak a widget in ilyStream, OBS does not always pick the change up
    immediately. Right-click the Browser Source in OBS and pick <em>Refresh
    cache of current page</em>.
  </p>

  <h2 id="troubleshooting">Troubleshooting</h2>
  <p><strong>OBS shows a blank source.</strong> Confirm the URL loads in a normal browser on the same PC. If it does not, the overlay server is not running or the port is blocked.</p>
  <p><strong>Source shows the URL with an error.</strong> ilyStream is probably not running. Start ilyStream and click <em>Refresh</em> on the source.</p>
  <p><strong>Animations stutter.</strong> Browser sources cost CPU. Drop the FPS to 30 if the machine is heavily loaded, or move the OBS process to a separate GPU.</p>
  <p><strong>Source still has a black background after editing CSS.</strong> Make sure <em>Shutdown source when not visible</em> is OFF and the page actually reloaded. Right-click &rarr; <em>Refresh cache</em>.</p>

